article.description: Jermaine O'Neal had 23 points and 14 rebounds to lead the Indiana Pacers to a 89-84 victory over the Detroit Pistons on Sunday.
article.headline: Pacers hand Pistons second consecutive loss
article.linkText: O'Neal helps Pacers squeak past Pistons
article.story:
AUBURN HILLS. Mich. (AP) -- The Indiana Pacers helped ease Isiah Thomas' uneasy feelings in his return to Detroit. Jermaine O'Neal had 23 points and 14 rebounds to lead the Pacers to a 89-84 victory over the Pistons on Sunday, snapping Indiana's two-game losing streak. Thomas, who spent his entire career playing in Detroit, returned to the Palace of Auburn Hills for the fourth time as a coach. "I really haven't felt like myself for the last couple days," Thomas said. "It's a good feeling, but it definitely has me off-balance when I come back here. I hope that never changes, because this city will always have a special place in my heart." A victory was foremost in the mind of the Pacers. "We had to grind this one out, but that's what we have been doing for the second half of the season," O'Neal said. "We are fighting for our lives right now." Ron Artest scored 16 points and Jamaal Tinsley added 15 for the Pacers. "This is a big win, because we have given away so many games lately," Artest said. "The Pistons have a great defensive team, so we knew it would be a low-scoring game, but we were able win a big one on the road." Reserve Corliss Williamson led the Pistons with 22 points. Jerry Stackhouse , bothered by a sore hip, scored just seven points, well under his 25 point average. Cliff Robinson finished with four points as Detroit lost its second straight and for the third time in four games. "I can't help us feeling like I'm feeling right now," Stackhouse said. "We've got a couple days off, and I just have to get well. I'm just not myself when it comes to scoring." Indiana limited Stackhouse and Robinson to 1-for-11 shooting in the first half and led 47-40 at the break. "Ronnie did a great job on Stackhouse, and that was the key," O'Neal said. "We played 48 minutes tonight -- that's what we haven't been doing." Chucky Atkins hit two 3-pointers and helped the Pistons close within 52-50 early in the third. The Pacers pushed their lead back to seven, but a 3-pointer by Michael Curry as time expired made it 68-64 game after three periods. Detroit opened the fourth period with a 7-2 run that included a pair of dunks by Ben Wallace and took a 71-70 lead. Indiana countered with eight straight points, including four by Jeff Foster, to take a 78-71 lead with 7:17 left. "That's the way we have been playing defensively since the trade with Chicago," Thomas said. "We've struggled with our offensive flow since getting those guys, but we've definitely been a tougher defensive team." Williamson made two baskets, but the Pacers then held Detroit scoreless for more than 3½ minutes to seal the victory. "I thought we certainly didn't play well," said Pistons coach Rick Carlisle. "I thought it was an uninspired performance by the team." Game notes
Wallace tied a Detroit record with five blocked shots in the first quarter. Terry Tyler had five blocks in a quarter twice in Feb. 1980, and John Salley did it in 1990. ... Zeljko Rebraca (broken eye socket) will be examined on Thursday, and the Pistons are hoping to have him back one week later. ... Jon Barry and Artest picked up technicals in the first quarter and Wallace got one for arguing a call. ... Detroit hadn't lost two straight games since a three-game slide in early January.
